Cape Town - In an effort to preserve memories and community voices, the Salt River Heritage Society (SRHS) launched a book on well-known and revered Cape Town musician Zayn Adam over the weekend.“Give A Little Love: The Zayn Adam Story” was launched at the Salt River Hall on Saturday. It’s named after his most famed track, “Give A Little Love”. The Salt River-born jazz artist died of a heart attack in Cape Town in 2015 at the age of 67. Adam was a member of the popular 1970s Cape Flats band, Pacific Express.Live music was performed by Adam’s son, Danyaal Adam, and brother Omar Adam, with his wife, Yadeema and sister-in-law in attendance.A panel discussion and Q&A session was held with University of Cape Town associate professor and SRHS member, Barbara Boswell, CEO of the Cornerstone Institute Noel Daniels and SRHS vice-chairperson Anwar Omar, and the author, Llewellin RG Jegels.MORE ON THISZayn Adam was ‘a humble legend’‘We are planning a grand tribute to Zayn’ –  DomingoLeft to right: Llewellin Jegels (author), Barbara Boswell (Associate Professor UCT and SRHS member), Noel Daniels (CEO Cornerstone Institute), Anwar Omar (Vice Chair SRHS), and MC Dimitri Jegels. Picture: Anwar Omar/SuppliedThe biography is based on Jegel’s Master’s thesis.“The fire that burnt deep inside of me, the fire that prompted me to write this biography, which, incidentally, is based on a Master’s thesis, arose from my deep and abiding passion not only for the story but revisionist stories, narratives that undo, unmake and uncreate.“Narratives that disrupt the status quo by re-centering indigenous voices, moving voices from the periphery to the centre, voices that may have been silent, or silenced. “This biography is such a narrative that seeks to preserve the late Zayn’s voice but still makes the connections with other artists, bands, personalities that formed part of the landscape, the tapestry of his life,” Jegel’s said.“In a sense, it is not only Zayn’s story but the story of all those other wonderful artists whose lives intersected with his for there can be no content without context. “And through this biography, we collectively celebrate his life by participating in the story through reading it, absorbing it and enjoying the invocation embedded in its very existence, an invitation to dance to the music he created, to listen again, and again, to the lyrics, the music that emanated from this legend, and, in so doing, to celebrate the legacy of Zayn Adam,” Jegel’s said.Omar said Zayn by all accounts had a deep connection with the area.“The SRHS records and documents the history and heritage of Salt River and Zayn’s life story forms part of the intangible heritage of the area.”The book will be available from Clarke’s Bookstore and others from the end of March, or contact the author directly on jegellr@unisa.ac.za.The Salt River born jazz artist, Zayn Adam, died of a heart attack in Cape Town in 2015, at the age of 67. Picture: Jeffrey Abrahams/African News Agency (ANA) Archivesshakirah.thebus@inl.co.zaCape Argus